Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament refused, in the context of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
The MPs refused in second reading the proposed amendment to reduce the penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having reached a disadvantageous prior agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The trial is not final and the court is due to rule on the defendant's appeal in December.
Tymosenko has qualified the judgment of political vengeance of the regime and has provoked a process of suspicions of bias of the court in the west as well.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
