MSS ad protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social Insurance conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by NPI specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Assurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of obesity of children and adolescents' that will allow the markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital des Specialités of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of physicians, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been trained.
This team is supported by third-cycle specialists and students of the National Institute of Public Health (NPI) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvesav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, it is invited to participate in the population with or without the right to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valle de México, where evidence is provided to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the sports unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Mexico West) and that, as of October 8, the activity takes place in the sports unit of Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
After achieving the objective of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of Federal District) and finally in the Sports Unit Morelos (north of Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that is to know the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for children and young Mexicans to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on 14 November on World Diabetes Day, he noted that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family legacy of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It has explained that Saturdays will be applied to all participants of anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of the size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (the aim is to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there was an increase in boys of 77 per cent in obesity and 47 per cent in girls of overweight; there was also a dramatic increase in overweights," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others by its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent indo-American inheritance, 30 per cent in Europe and five per cent in Africa, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess of energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full evaluation of children, which enables them to detect if they present a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored plus (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and doctors send it in writing to parents, to whom each is explained the measures and changes in the lifestyle they have to make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the largest consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pasta to corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cassia
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemicals School, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mix with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand rainfalls each rainy season in the Métropolitan Area of Valle de México, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemie (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the casses could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory responsible for it develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the performance, and consequently, the formation of casses.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltene, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give to the paveda its viscoelastic behavior characteristic.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents a almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes cassant, adds it.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City in most of them were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the small stones that forms the bed, it indicates, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles go through with efforts, it allows the forces to propagate very well into the pavement.
If the asphalt had changed, the asphalt would propagate better, the chemical engineer would.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one last layer called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adherence to the street.
As the part of the deck that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made of should be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, as they significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to do, which boils all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassis.
In the process of forming a cassia, he says, the first one that breaks is the rolling film and only later the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated at the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassia and therefore the thickness of each layer of the deck must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent training of cassia.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow for easy repair of casses and without having to use high temperatures.
