Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says an expert committee.
Canadians live in the denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of an impressive report of the Royal Society of Canada, with six experts involved in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code so as to enable assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the planet.
If Canada has ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, they report to us experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them eventually die at the hospital.
Overall, in Quebec, this rate is the highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring at the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report arrive at conclusions that are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already said they do not want to change anything to the Criminal Code on Euthanasia and Assisted Suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide assisted by non-compliant or non-consent persons.
On the contrary, it stated yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, co-signator of the report, there would be more cases of these spillovers precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"The assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie says.
Canadians Supporting Euthanasia
Let us recall that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia because they believe that it would allow end-of-life people to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
