In his program, François Hollande can boast banality, indicating that co-development will solve our "migrant problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electoral pay, but it is economically very expensive.
As noted by economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Definition Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration undermines growth and reduces employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may replace national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, with lower pressures on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly in job shortages sectors.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the job supply.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anaesthetics, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
