North Stream, Russia's new gas port in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia by crossing the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with bursts.
More than 500 guests, of whom four heads of state and government participated, on Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly under the sea to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Filon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube connecting the region of St. Petersburg to the Land of Mecklembourg-Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same course.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has air of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will enable gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossings by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to the West European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supply.
But it is at the price of a weakening of Europe of energy, as the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has barely achieved its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," confirmed François Filon, opening this gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major gas contracts are both political and economic.
This explains the broad smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical operation.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-gained steel to protect it against ships' anchors.
It rests on the seabed at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, by caution," said Jens Müller, spokesman of North Stream.
There was also a need to multiply the measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts all its length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A monitoring platform was planned off Sweden, but project managers resigned from it while the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state company established permanently off their shores.
"In case of damage, we stop passing the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline is thus leaked into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to escape every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, trained by a ship, for external observation, and by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
Of the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide by one meter diameter, and is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, he provides accurate information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run fifty years without having to suffer less repair.
Gas circulation is simply driven by pressure.
It is 200 bars in the beginning, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, holding 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) and the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this renewable 20-year company the total gas transport capacity.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of actually transported gas," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be up to EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their fees, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters tall, form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand name card.
