Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy set up in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is even greater than average: 19%, compared with 9% for the whole population.
Discouragement?
"No, Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the Association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
" The progress made over the past 15 years has been considerable " .
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"It remains, however, enormously to be done."
It must be said that for disabled people, the obstacles remain much before they can get to employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the bac and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that specifically complicate the return to employment, and which "are the core of the problem," said Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
There remains the non-dict, the mindsets that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur for the City indicated that the interviewed managers had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, the private companies of more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% disabled workers, as set out in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures from 2008 show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46,000 (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
" The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc. "
" But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of the 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of the companies from 100 to 199 employees.
